    "narrative": "For our April 22nd slate, **Tyler Freeman** (72.83) stands out as our premier start. His matchup against Buehler is statistically advantageous, buoyed by an elite 14% park factor and the pitcher's high expected ERA. Crucially, we are tracking Buehler\u2019s slow delivery, which projects to offer **Tyler Freeman** a +2% boost in stolen base potential\u2014an essential metric given our scarcity-driven strategy. Following close behind are **Gleyber Torres** (67.46) and **Wenceel Perez** (66.02), both of whom capitalize on a +19% SP skill advantage against Hall. **Gleyber Torres** in particular benefits from a favorable platoon split, making him an anchor for our lineup tonight.\n\nWe are navigating several high-leverage situations, most notably the decision to bench **Matt Chapman** (48.41). Despite his pedigree, **Matt Chapman** is suppressed by an elite matchup against Ohtani, whose 2.67 xERA drags down the entire projected output for that game. Consequently, we are favoring the volume and platoon context of our middle-of-the-order hitters. We remain cautious regarding **Luis Arraez** (48.80) and **Geraldo Perdomo** (49.77), both of whom also draw Ohtani or similarly difficult arms; they remain in the lineup only due to their projected floor, but we are ready to pull the plug if game caps become an issue.\n\nThe biggest risks for the day center on the weather conditions. While we have baked a +5% \"Wind Out\" boost into the scores for **Will Smith**, **Taylor Ward**, and **Jeremiah Jackson**, any late-shift in stadium gusts could negate that efficiency. Furthermore, we are keeping a close eye on **Jos\u00e9 Ram\u00edrez** (54.48). While his raw talent is indisputable, his score is currently dampened by a tough matchup against Lambert. We are confident in our current configuration, but we will be monitoring the late-game replacements for **Jonathan Aranda**, whose platoon-heavy profile could lead to an early exit if the game gets out of hand.",
